Lecture 2. Tissue Structure and Function: Part I (Elisseeff)
Thursday, Feburary 1st, 2018
These lectures will introduce the basic structure of tissue in the body. In the tissues covered, students should be able to recognize a tissue morphologically (from histological sections) and understand the basic structure of each tissue and its relation to function. Tissues covered include vascular, muscle, nerve, connective, GI, liver, kidney.

Kidney - analogous to the shape of spaghetti and meatball
Each kidney has a ureter, which drains urine from the kidney's central collecting area (renal pelvis) into the bladder. From the bladder, urine drains through the urethra, out of the body through the penis in males and the vulva in females.
Each kidney contains about a million filtering units called nephrons. A nephron begins as a hollow-walled, bowl-like structure (Bowman's capsule), which contains a tuft of blood vessels (the glomerulus). Collectively, these two structures are called a renal corpuscle.
Pancreas
The islets of Langerhans
constitute the endocrine portion of the pancreas. Three types of cells are identifiable within the islets.
The (small) beta cells make up about 75% of the islet, occupy the interior of the island, and secrete insulin.

What is a stem cell? (2)

Division of stem cells
stemness is a continuum —> a rough classification that is hard to always characterize stem with a clean cut between different cell stages
asymmetric division —> self renewal of parent and production of a daughter cell that can differentiate
symmetric divison
clonal reproduction of parent
two daughters that differentiate and loss of stemness

What does it mean?

Tissue engineering using ES cells
Growth factor, Electrical stimulation - conduction (cause the cell beating)

Neural - Stem cells with brainpower (2 Nature papers)
Methods
Reubinoff (ES cell culture --> 3 weeks overgrowth, pick out neural rosettes, make neural spheres and expose to bFGF and EGF)
Zhang (EBs 4 days, plate EBs and expose to bFGF 8-10 days, enzymatically remove neural rosettes and form neural spheres.
In vivo – both groups performed xenograft studies —> transplanted aggregates into lateral ventricle of neonate rats.
Cells found in cortex, thalamus, striatum, hippocampus, hypothalamus, and midbrain. Morphological indistinguishable from host (no function tested). No teratomas
Characterization. (2)
No oligodendrocytes (cells that surround/support neurons in CNS).

Reprogramming cells
it’s not easy to do it.
Using traditional method, only 3-5% of cells expressing the reprogramming factors become pluripotent.
Emerge after 1-2 weeks. (time consuming)
Barriers are apoptosis, senescence and cell cycle arrest. Proliferating cells seem to do better – and somatic expression must be blocked before the conversion. Residual epigenetic memory may impact function.
To make iPSCs more clinically applicable, various non-integrating methods have been developed to circumvent the risk of insertional mutagenesis and genetic alterations associated with retroviral and lentiviral transduction-mediated introduction of reprogramming factors205.

Non-therapeutic use of iPSCs
modeling disease and enhancing drug development. Avior review, nature reviews molecular cell biology, 2016
iPSC benefit over mouse models.
Used for studying monogenic (single gene) disorders and complex disorders, early and late onset. 
Monogenic diseases can also be modeled by gene editing of healthy cells
Late onset disease more difficult to study – prefer mouse models of the disease or induce cellular aging.
some diseases require more advanced culturing techniques. By modelling ALS using cocultures of neurons and glial cells77,78, it was shown that spinal motor neurons are selectively sensitive to the toxic effects of glial cells carrying a mutant SOD1 gene. It is interesting to note that this effect was not apparent when culturing neurons with fibroblasts expressing mutant SOD1, confirming the specificity of the model78.

How do you isolate MSCs?
MSCs make up 0.001-0.01% of cells in bone marrow.
One method
Aspirate bone marrow (usually from iliac crest, cells differ depending on isolation site).
MSCs will adhere to TCP, spread, and proliferate (blood cells die out).
Takes about 2 weeks for cells from aspirate to “take off”.
Others use a density gradient to isolate cells.
Serum lot is important and affects differentiation.
No conditions for infinite culture.
compositions of the media can make a difference
hard to reproduce
What are standard MSC differentiation capability
Multi-potential capabilities of cells are often characterized by standard assays to look at adipogenic, osteogenic, and chondrogenic differentiation. Example of a control is a standard fibroblast cell line. Differentiation occurs in 1-3 weeks.
Adipogenic
In monolayer culture induce with dexamethasone, insulin, indomethacin, and 1-methyl-3-isobutylxanthine.
Outcome
expression of peroxisome proliferation activated receptor gamma2 (PPARg2),
LPL (lipoprotein lipase)
fatty acid binding protein
Histology staining – Oil Red O (stains lipid in vacuoles red)
Chondrogenic
micromass culture with TGFß (pellet + TGFß), no serum.
Outcome
Type II collagen
thick ECM
SafraninO staining
red/orange staining of negatively charged proteoglycans
Osteogenic —> alizarin stain red
monolayer culture with dexamethasone (steroid), b-glycerophosphate, and ascorbate (with serum).
outcome
Alkaline phosphatase (ALP)≥ activity
calcium accumulation
vonKossa staining for calcium
Application to cardiac repair
MSCs injected intracardiac (around infarct) or systemically infused (engraftment depends on time after injury).
better ejection fraction
Researchers at Osiris found MScs prevented pathological wall thickening post MI, decr end diastolic pressure (no systolic improvement). Generally prevents pathological remodeling (scar).
Also found MSCs expressed endothelial and vasc markers (imp for revascularization of heart). Some find cardiac markers of MSCs, others don’t.
Recruitment of MSCs to sites of injury in vivo testing
MSCs appear to hone to areas of damage. Shown nicely in paper Rosenthal.
GFP-labeled MSCs in mouse (with IGF mutation). Injected toxin in muscle to damage the tissue – then looked which cells were there (GFP) and what markers they expressed (Sca-1, Desmin, myf 5 and other muscle markers). Similar experiments performed for cardiac applications.
How do you track cells without changing their behavior?
Cells can be labeled with GFP, Lac-Z, tritiated H, magnetic particles (argument over change in cell behavior).
Immunological aspects of MSCs.
MSCs have MHC Class I but not Class II receptors (important for recognizing foreign cells).
MSCs do not carry co-stimulatory molecules either.
MHC Class II receptors are not induced by differentiation but can be by IFN-gamma.
MSCs also carry immunosuppressive properties.
MSCs do not elicit T-cell proliferation or activation in MLR (mixed lymphocyte reaction).
They even suppress T-cell response when a 3rd party donor cell is added.
One researcher compared the suppression to cyclosporine. Found to be a soluble factor produced by MSCs that is responsible for this behavior.
Flexibility of MSCs
We are still understanding the true differentiation capabilities of these cells.
There is evidence that MSCs can differentiate into cells from all germ layers and when injected/transplanted are found in all tissues.
This needs to be confirmed since there are issues of fusion and simply presence in the vascular network.
Concept of transgermal plasticity
Important issues to consider
cell selection versus differentiation, fusion…
Clinical note
MSCs cotransplanted wit hHSCs improve bone marrow transplant outcome. MSCs secrete factors to important to marrow microenvironment that support hematopoiesis and help engraftment.
Other clinical testing of MSCs
GVH
Crohns
essentially any inflammatory disease

Structurally, gelatin molecules contain repeating sequences of glycine-X-Y triplets, where X and Y are frequently proline and hydroxyproline amino acids. These sequences are responsible for the triple helical structure of gelatin and its ability to form gels where helical regions form in the gelatin protein chains immobilizing water.
